  "output": "## Analysis Summary\n\nThis is a Python codebase (async ATS scraper → SQLite dedup store → notifiers), not a web app — there's no React/JS frontend, so \"unnecessary re-renders\" doesn't apply here. `sources.yaml` configures **114 companies**, several with `max_pages` up to 40 (10-16 jobs/page), so a full run can produce tens of thousands of `Job` objects flowing through `filter_jobs` and `Store.diff` — that scale is exactly where the two real findings below start to hurt.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-97` (`Store.diff`)\n\nEvery job does its own `SELECT`, then its own `INSERT`/`UPDATE` — one SQLite round trip per row, in a Python-level loop, for potentially tens of thousands of jobs per run.\n\n```python\n# current: N SELECTs + N INSERT/UPDATE, one row at a time\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job); self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    ...\n```\n\n**Fix:** load all existing `(key, content_hash)` pairs once, diff in Python, then batch-write with `executemany`:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing = dict(self.conn.execute(\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs\"))\n\n    new, changed, unchanged_keys = [], [], []\n    insert_rows, update_rows = [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        row_hash = existing.get(job.key)\n        r = {**job.to_row(), \"now\": now}\n        if row_hash is None:\n            new.append(job); insert_rows.append(r)\n        elif row_hash != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); update_rows.append(r)\n        else:\n            unchanged_keys.append(job.key)\n\n    if insert_rows:\n        self.conn.executemany(\n            \"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (key, source, company, external_id, title, url,\n                 location, department, employment_type, posted_at, salary_range,\n                 content_hash, first_seen, last_seen)\n               VALUES (:key,:source,:company,:external_id,:title,:url,:location,\n                 :department,:employment_type,:posted_at,:salary_range,\n                 :content_hash,:now,:now)\"\"\", insert_rows)\n    if update_rows:\n        self.conn.executemany(\n            \"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET title=:title, url=:url, location=:location,\n                 department=:department, employment_type=:employment_type,\n                 posted_at=:posted_at, salary_range=:salary_range,\n                 content_hash=:content_hash, last_seen=:now WHERE key=:key\"\"\", update_rows)\n    if unchanged_keys:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\",\n                               [(now, k) for k in unchanged_keys])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\n`jobs.db` is small enough (348 KB) that loading the whole `key → content_hash` map costs one cheap query instead of thousands.\n\nThis also removes the redundant computation you get today for free: `job.content_hash` (a SHA-256 hash) currently gets computed twice per changed job — once for the comparison, once again inside `_update`'s call to `job.to_row()`. Computing `r = job.to_row()` once up front, as above, fixes both issues in one pass.\n\n### 2. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-41` (regex recompiled per job)\n\n`match()` calls `_compile(include)` and `_compile(exclude)` on *every job*, recompiling the identical regex list from scratch each time — for a 10,000-job run with 5 keywords, that's 50,000 unnecessary `re.compile` calls for a fixed set of patterns.\n\n```python\n# current\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):  # recompiled every call\n```\n\n**Fix:** compile once in `filter_jobs` and pass the compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          exclude: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          locations: list[str] | None = None,\n          cutoff: datetime | None = None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    if locations:\n        loc = job.location.lower()\n        if not any(l.lower() in loc for l in locations):\n            return False\n    if cutoff is not None:\n        dt = job.posted_dt\n        if dt is not None and dt < cutoff:\n            return False\n    return True\n\n\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\n### Other categories checked, nothing actionable found\n\n- **Caching (HTTP):** `fetch_all` already shares a single `httpx.AsyncClient` across all 114 sources with a bounded `Semaphore` — connection pooling is handled correctly, no change needed.\n- **Memory leaks:** `Store` and `httpx.AsyncClient` are consistently used via context managers (`with Store(...)`, `owns_client` guard in `fetch_all`) or closed explicitly — nothing unclosed.\n- **React re-renders:** not applicable — no frontend in this repo.\n- **Minor/non-actionable:** `notify.dispatch()` makes blocking `httpx.post`/SMTP calls synchronously at the tail of an async `run()` — it only runs once after all fetches complete, so it doesn't block concurrency; not worth the complexity of making it async for a personal single-run CLI tool.\n\nWant me to apply the two fixes above (`store.py` batching + `filters.py` regex precompilation)?\n",
